🔁 Fork

A fork is done on a platform like GitHub (or GitLab, Bitbucket).

It creates a copy of someone else’s repository in your own account.
Used when you don’t have direct write access or want your own version.
Common in open-source contributions.

👉 Example:
You fork a repo → now you have your own version under your GitHub profile.

💻 Clone

A clone is a Git command you run locally.

It downloads a repository (your own or someone else’s) to your computer.
Creates a working copy with full history.

👉 Command:

git clone https://github.com/user/repo.git
🔑 Key Differences
| Feature          | Fork                                   | Clone                              |
| ---------------- | -------------------------------------- | ---------------------------------- |
| Where it happens | Online (GitHub)                        | Local machine                      |
| Purpose          | Copy repo to your account              | Copy repo to your computer         |
| Ownership        | You own the fork                       | Same repo, just local copy         |
| Use case         | Contributing / modifying independently | Development, editing, running code |
